<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06021168 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06021168 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; Associated Press; Crew from USS Saratoga in Red Sea loads a missile onF-14 Tomcat  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  MIDEAST; WAR; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The sea war in the Persian Gulf has produced two firsts in the history ofmodern warfare.;    On Saturday, a submarine launched a cruise missile on acombat mission. The night before, a new computer-guided, standoff missilecalled a SLAM hit a combat target.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GULF SEA WAR ACHIEVES TWO FIRSTS'SMART WEAPON,' SUBMARINE CRUISE MISSILELAUNCHED  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  WAR IN THE GULFMideast Roundup  </MEMO><TEXT>     The cruise missile was fired from a submarine in either the Persian Gulf orthe Red Sea and aimed at a target in Iraq, according to Rear Adm. Riley D.Mixson, commander of the Red Sea battle force. He refused to name thesubmarine.;    Cruise missiles, which are pilotless, low-flying jets, can befired from battleships, cruisers and submarines.;    The SLAM missile is a&quot;smart weapon&quot; outfitted with a camera, which transmits target images back toa crew member in a plane a safe distance from enemy anti-aircraft fire. Mixsonsaid two SLAM missiles scored direct hits on what he called &quot;a well-defendedindustrial-type target.&quot;;     IRAQ CANCELS PACTS WITH SAUDI ARABIA; NICOSIA,Cyprus -- Iraq today canceled all bilateral accords with Saudi Arabia,including a non-aggression pact.;    The official Iraqi News Agency said in adispatch monitored in Nicosia that the decision was made at a meeting of theruling Revolutionary Command Council under President Saddam Hussein.;    Theagency quoted a council statement as saying: &quot;Iraq has decided to abrogate alltreaties and agreements with Saudi Arabia, irrespective of their nature andincluding the joint non-aggression pact.&quot;;    It said the decision was madeafter the neighboring kingdom &quot;violated these accords by joining thetreacherous aggression launched by the United States and its allied Atlanticforces against Iraq.&quot;;     CANADA'S WAR ENTRY ITS FIRST SINCE KOREA; TORONTO-- Canada mounted its first official offensive missions of the gulf warSunday, the first time in 40 years -- since the Korean War -- that Canadianforces have been sent into battle.;    Canadian CF-18 warplanes took off fromtheir bases in the Persian Gulf sheikdom of Qatar to join U.S. planes on&quot;sweep and escort&quot; missions over Iraq and Kuwait. Heavy clouds forced thefirst planes to turn back, but the Canadians are due to continue the missionswhen the weather clears.;     ORDER SET FOR 2ND TIER OF ARMY RESERVISTS;WASHINGTON -- The Army said Sunday it is calling up about 20,000 members ofthe Individual Ready Reserve, the second-tier pool of military reservists, toprovide special skills in support of the Persian Gulf war.;    They mustreport for duty Jan. 31 and can be kept on duty for up to one year.;    It isthe first time since the Vietnam War that members of Individual Ready Reservehave been ordered to active duty, and it is the largest such call-up since theKorean War.;     QUESTIONS SURFACE AS CNN STAYS IN IRAQ; Washington -- CableNews Network correspondent Peter Arnett was America's last remaining link withIraq on Sunday, but the conditions under which he was allowed to stay raisedquestions about whether he had been made the voice of Baghdad.;    Arnett, aveteran war correspondent, could file only when Iraqi officials let him andcould say only what they permitted.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  ABOARD THE USS JOHN F. KENNEDY IN THE RED SEA  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910121  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  13A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  